Transit exploratory analysis

Aaron Berdanier

2017-07-01

Setup

I am excited about helping people understand and use data. I think that there are great opportunities to answer interesting questions in public transportation with data.

For an example, I explored data from Durham County to look at two main questions:

  1. How far is each building in Durham County from a transit stop?
  2. Where can I go from my house with one or fewer transfers?
    • Also, can I get to TransLoc? (spoiler: yes)
library(dplyr)
library(httr)
library(leaflet)
library(readr)
library(sf)

# Helper functions
stack_gtfs <- function(dlist, fname, ...){
  ll <- lapply(file.path(dlist, fname), read_csv, ...)
  Reduce(function(df1, df2) rbind(df1, df2), ll)
}
google_geocode <- function(address, api_key){
  urlbase <- "https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json"
  u <- paste0(urlbase, "?address=", gsub("\ ","%20",address), "&key=", api_key)
  r <- GET(u)
  coord <- data.frame(content(r)$results[[1]]$geometry$location)
  # need x,y, so reverse the result
  return(rev(coord))
}

Bring in data on building locations and GoDurham routes

# Durham County buildings
# Downloaded from https://opendurham.nc.gov/explore/dataset/buildings0/
buildings <- st_read("buildings0.kml")
build_geom <- st_geometry(buildings)
# Transform to UTM 17N (http://spatialreference.org/ref/epsg/32617/)
build_utm <- st_transform(build_geom, 32617)
# Find center of each building
build <- st_centroid(build_utm)

# GTFS data
# Downloaded from http://godurhamtransit.org/developer-resources/gtfs
# Directories for different agencies
dd <- list.dirs("GTFS", recursive=F)
# Load the stop points
stops_in <- stack_gtfs(dd, "stops.txt")
# Get the coordinates of the stops
stops_xy <- as.matrix(select(stops_in, stop_lon, stop_lat))
# probably a better way to do this... but turn them into a "st" object
stops_list <- lapply(1:nrow(stops_xy), function(i) st_point(stops_xy[i,]))
stops_geom <- st_sfc(stops_list)
# Set and transform coordinate reference
st_crs(stops_geom) <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"
stops <- st_transform(stops_geom, 32617)
# Load trips
trips_in <- stack_gtfs(dd, "trips.txt")
# Load routes
routes_in <- stack_gtfs(dd, "routes.txt")
# Load stop_times
stop_times_in <- stack_gtfs(dd, "stop_times.txt",
  col_types=cols(arrival_time=col_character(), departure_time=col_character()))
# I converted the times this way because read_csv was giving me special errors
stop_times_in$arrival_time <- parse_time(stop_times_in$arrival_time)
stop_times_in$departure_time <- parse_time(stop_times_in$departure_time)
# join stop codes and trip ids to the stop times
stop_times_in <- full_join(stop_times_in, select(stops_in, stop_id, stop_code))
stop_times_in <- full_join(stop_times_in, select(trips_in, route_id, trip_id))

1. Get distance from nearest transit stop for each building in Durham County

# Euclidean distance between all buildings and all stops - "as the crow flies"
dist_all <- st_distance(build, stops)
# distance to closest stop
dist_min <- apply(dist_all, 1, function(i) i[which.min(i)])
stop_dist <- st_sf(distance=log(dist_min), build)

# convert to long-lat for plotting in leaflet
llstopdist <- st_transform(stop_dist, 4326)
# color palette for plot
pal <- colorNumeric("RdYlBu", range(log(dist_min)), reverse=T)
# random subsample for plotting
plot_subsample <- sample_n(llstopdist, 15000)
# Map of distance to a transit stop for each building in Durham County
leaflet(data=plot_subsample) %>% addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(radius=3, fillColor=~pal(distance), fillOpacity=1, stroke=F) %>%
  addLegend(position="topright", pal=pal, values=~distance,
  labFormat=labelFormat(transform=exp, digits=0), title="Distance (m)")

Red areas are priority zones for other services that could enhance access

(I chose a random subsample to display because there are >100k points)

2. Find all destinations within one transfer of my house

# Combine all stops with feature data
stops_all <- st_sf(stops_in, geometry=stops_geom)
# start point, my house
my_address <- "2408 Huron St., Durham, NC 27707"
me_xy <- google_geocode(my_address, api_key)
me_geom <- st_sfc(st_point(as.numeric(me_xy)))
st_crs(me_geom) <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"
me <- st_transform(me_geom, 32617)
# Get the stop closest to me
stops_me <- st_distance(me, stops)
my_stop <- stops_all[which.min(stops_me),]

These are the departures from the closest bus stop to my house.

# All departure times from my stop by route id
filter(stop_times_in, stop_code==my_stop$stop_code) %>%
  arrange(departure_time) %>%
  select(route_id, departure_time) %>% distinct()

These are the end points within one transfer

## Zero order connections
# Trips that stop at my stop
trips_l0 <- stop_times_in %>%
  filter(stop_id == my_stop$stop_id) %>% distinct(trip_id)
 # Stop points for those trips
stops_l0 <- stop_times_in %>%
  filter(trip_id %in% trips_l0$trip_id) %>% distinct(stop_code)
## First order connections
# Routes that stop at those stops
routes_l1 <- stop_times_in %>%
  filter(stop_code %in% stops_l0$stop_code) %>% distinct(route_id)
# Endpoints on those routes
stops_l1 <- stop_times_in %>%
  filter(route_id %in% routes_l1$route_id) %>% distinct(stop_code)
# The stops that I can access in one or fewer transfers
my_stops_all <- filter(stops_all, stop_code %in% stops_l1$stop_code)

3. Map where I can go in one stop or less

# destination; TransLoc
transloc_address <- "4505 Emperor Blvd Suite 120, Durham, NC 27703"
transloc_xy <- google_geocode(transloc_address, api_key)
transloc_geom <- st_sfc(st_point(as.numeric(transloc_xy)))
st_crs(transloc_geom) <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"
transloc <- st_transform(transloc_geom, 32617)
# Plot
leaflet(data=st_geometry(my_stops_all)) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(radius=3, fillOpacity=1, stroke=F) %>%
  addMarkers(label="Aaron's house", data=me_geom) %>%
  addMarkers(label="TransLoc", data=transloc_geom)

Blue points are stops within one transfer from my house

Plus, the markers are my house and TransLocs office.
